1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:01,680
This is Justin.

2
00:00:01,680 --> 00:00:07,279
He built his online business to $1.7 million a year, working only five hours a day.

3
00:00:07,279 --> 00:00:10,080
And the crazy part is he runs it all by himself.

4
00:00:10,080 --> 00:00:11,519
I don't have any employees.

5
00:00:11,519 --> 00:00:16,080
What's even more insane is the story of why he decided to quit his job to do this.

6
00:00:16,080 --> 00:00:18,320
Screaming, crying, hallucinating.

7
00:00:18,320 --> 00:00:19,600
Didn't know what was happening.

8
00:00:19,600 --> 00:00:26,320
In this episode, we met up in downtown New York City, and he showed me exactly how he makes millions of dollars with zero employees.

9
00:00:26,320 --> 00:00:29,039
Last year, my business did about 1.7 million.

10
00:00:29,039 --> 00:00:32,559
Uh, and this year I anticipate that it'll do around two and a half.

11
00:00:32,559 --> 00:00:37,440
He also told me the secrets to getting hundreds of thousands of followers on Twitter and LinkedIn.

12
00:00:37,440 --> 00:00:46,480
It's not as complex, I think, as a lot of folks might assume that it is, and how he runs his entire business on less than $700.

13
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:49,680
The total cost of my business is about 620 bucks a month.

14
00:00:49,680 --> 00:00:55,199
This interview is a master class on how to build a multi-million dollar oneperson business from scratch.

15
00:00:55,199 --> 00:00:59,840
I'm Pat Walls and this is Starter Story.

16
00:00:59,840 --> 00:01:04,320
All right, Justin, can you explain to the audience exactly what you do and how you make money?

17
00:01:04,320 --> 00:01:09,920
So, the the easiest way to describe it is I have sort of a portfolio of products that I sell.

18
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:14,640
Uh my main portfolio is what you would just call online courses or information products.

19
00:01:14,640 --> 00:01:15,760
I sell two of those.

20
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:20,960
One on how to use LinkedIn effectively to build a business and the other one on how to build your own content system.

21
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:26,159
A secondary way that I make money is I have a newsletter that's approaching 100,000 subscribers.

22
00:01:26,159 --> 00:01:35,439
So, I sell sponsorships to companies who want to get in front of, you know, their ideal customer if that person or or group of people happen to be my readership.

23
00:01:35,439 --> 00:01:46,479
And then a third way that I make money is I have a subscription email that I send out where every month they'll get an email from me that shows them uh copywriting techniques for for writing better copy on social media.

24
00:01:46,479 --> 00:01:56,000
So all in all, everything that I do is based on knowledge and uh I most commonly refer to myself as a knowledge entrepreneur when people uh you know don't know exactly what I do.

25
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,320
Based on all these products, how much money do you make total?

26
00:01:58,320 --> 00:02:01,520
Uh last year my business did about 1.7 million.

27
00:02:01,520 --> 00:02:05,119
Uh and this year I anticipate that it'll do around 2 and a half.

28
00:02:05,119 --> 00:02:10,160
So I think it's it's hard for some people to comprehend that one person, you're just one person,

29
00:02:10,160 --> 00:02:13,120
no team, can make $1.7 million a year.

30
00:02:13,120 --> 00:02:14,480
How is that even possible?

31
00:02:14,480 --> 00:02:19,360
I think the most important thing to think about if you can commit to getting on social media,

32
00:02:19,360 --> 00:02:28,400
choosing a topic you're passionate about, really educating yourself about it, and then going out and writing consistently about it every single day on multiple platforms,

33
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:32,000
sometimes two to three times per day, then you can build up this audience.

34
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,560
And then it really becomes a numbers game, right?

35
00:02:34,560 --> 00:02:43,360
If you have a million followers and 1% or 2% of your 1 million followers buy a product that you offer at a few hundred,

36
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:48,319
well, suddenly you see that this becomes relatively possible when you add to the mix tools,

37
00:02:48,319 --> 00:02:49,920
systems, and processes.

38
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:51,840
It becomes significantly easier.

39
00:02:51,840 --> 00:02:56,400
So, you can't just wake up every day as a oneperson business and say, well, what do I do on Monday?

40
00:02:56,400 --> 00:02:57,280
What do I do on Tuesday?

41
00:02:57,280 --> 00:02:58,319
What do I do on Wednesday?

42
00:02:58,319 --> 00:03:01,599
When I wake up every morning during the week, I know exactly what I'm doing.

43
00:03:01,599 --> 00:03:03,599
And then it's a lot of tools, right?

44
00:03:03,599 --> 00:03:07,200
like publishing tools which allow you to schedule your your social media publishing,

45
00:03:07,200 --> 00:03:11,440
tools like notion which allows you to stay organized and have all your ideas in one place.

46
00:03:11,440 --> 00:03:16,959
Tools like Trello which allows you to, you know, move projects forward and these are things that I leverage,

47
00:03:16,959 --> 00:03:18,879
you know, on a regular basis for my business.

48
00:03:18,879 --> 00:03:21,040
And I know you have a pretty unique background.

49
00:03:21,040 --> 00:03:26,800
Can you tell me about what you were doing before this and the journey that led you to where you're at today?

50
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:36,400
Yeah, prior to going online and and building a business, I was in technology and ended up at a really small tech firm in New York called Zakdoc.

51
00:03:36,400 --> 00:03:45,840
And um I was successful out of the gate and spent 5 years at that company eventually reporting to the CEO and I parlayed that into my very first executive role at 33.

52
00:03:45,840 --> 00:03:47,040
I was the VP of sales.

53
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:52,000
I was hired on, but I was the VP of sales of one person in a company that had no revenue.

54
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:59,840
And I thought I would do maybe 1 or 3 million in ARR and they would go get like an inexperienced person to come kind of take over that that role.

55
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:01,280
Hired some good people.

56
00:04:01,280 --> 00:04:02,720
A lot of things just went my way.

57
00:04:02,720 --> 00:04:06,000
And the company grew to about 50 million in recurring in 4 and a half years.

58
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:12,560
The problem is that when you work at a company like Zachdoc, which was really, really well known for like very cutthroat,

59
00:04:12,560 --> 00:04:17,040
very, very deep and intense work ethic, and then transition into becoming an executive,

60
00:04:17,040 --> 00:04:24,320
you go 10 consecutive years of high anxiety, high stress, board meetings, targets, and after 10 years,

61
00:04:24,320 --> 00:04:25,919
um, I burned out really badly.

62
00:04:25,919 --> 00:04:33,040
And that all culminated in this massive panic attack that I had on December would have been December 16th of 2018,

63
00:04:33,040 --> 00:04:35,199
um, where I just thought I was dying.

64
00:04:35,199 --> 00:04:38,479
For people who have had panic attacks, your fingers go numb is the first thing.

65
00:04:38,479 --> 00:04:44,400
Then you get very confused and like I was on all fours, screaming, crying, hallucinating.

66
00:04:44,400 --> 00:04:45,680
Didn't know what was happening.

67
00:04:45,680 --> 00:04:55,759
Uh so my wife called 911 and uh the EMTs came out and told me that I was not dying and uh things subsided over the next few hours and that was the end of my career in tech.

68
00:04:55,759 --> 00:05:03,560
Basically, that was how I ended up trying to build my own thing on social media.

69
00:05:07,520 --> 00:05:11,759
I know you run a oneperson business, so you can't spend too much money.

70
00:05:11,759 --> 00:05:14,240
What do you spend money on and what don't you spend money on?

71
00:05:14,240 --> 00:05:14,800
Yeah.

72
00:05:14,800 --> 00:05:18,080
Um, I spend mostly on software.

73
00:05:18,080 --> 00:05:21,280
So, um, I try and keep my software stack as lean as possible.

74
00:05:21,280 --> 00:05:28,160
I use a a piece of software called Kajjabi, which is sort of like an all-in-one marketing solution and website solution for,

75
00:05:28,160 --> 00:05:31,039
you know, solarreneurs, creators, coaches, things like that.

76
00:05:31,039 --> 00:05:35,280
So that is the primary meat of my cost, 399 bucks a month.

77
00:05:35,280 --> 00:05:38,560
The total cost of my business is about 620 bucks a month.

78
00:05:38,560 --> 00:05:43,600
Uh so I have things like testimonial.to, I've got Tapio, I have Hype Furious, some publishing tools.

79
00:05:43,600 --> 00:05:47,759
Uh almost everything that I invest into my business is tools.

80
00:05:47,759 --> 00:05:50,639
I do not spend any money on paid ads.

81
00:05:50,639 --> 00:05:52,240
So I've never run a paid ad before.

82
00:05:52,240 --> 00:05:53,919
I don't have any employees.

83
00:05:53,919 --> 00:05:57,520
Um I very very rarely work with freelancers and contractors.

84
00:05:57,520 --> 00:06:06,240
But I really spend most of my money on software and things that make creating content easier for me cuz my business is really content driven.

85
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:07,199
All right, let's get tactical.

86
00:06:07,199 --> 00:06:08,560
I want to talk about marketing.

87
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:14,479
You've reached millions, potentially billions of impressions on social media and you've sold millions of courses.

88
00:06:14,479 --> 00:06:16,160
What's your marketing strategy?

89
00:06:16,160 --> 00:06:21,280
It's not as complex, I think, as a lot of folks might assume that it is.

90
00:06:21,280 --> 00:06:22,800
Really, it's content driven.

91
00:06:22,800 --> 00:06:29,280
Most of my strategy is to show up on two platforms every single day, two to three times a day.

92
00:06:29,280 --> 00:06:32,240
And those platforms right now are LinkedIn and Twitter.

93
00:06:32,240 --> 00:06:36,000
And the way that I do that is sort of a few different things.

94
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:38,319
The first one is what I call discovery.

95
00:06:38,319 --> 00:06:42,960
And that is just getting discovered by new people at the top of funnel.

96
00:06:42,960 --> 00:06:47,680
So on Twitter, on LinkedIn, people who have never discovered me, who have no idea who I am,

97
00:06:47,680 --> 00:06:52,479
who have never seen my name and face before, I want them to find me on those social media platforms.

98
00:06:52,479 --> 00:06:58,160
The second thing that I want to do once people have discovered me, and this is sort of the second part of my I guess you could call it funnel,

99
00:06:58,160 --> 00:07:01,520
but I don't really like to think of it as a funnel, is trust.

100
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:05,680
And trust to me comes from really showing people how your brain works.

101
00:07:05,680 --> 00:07:09,919
And the easiest way to show someone how your brain works is through longer form content.

102
00:07:09,919 --> 00:07:14,720
So what that is for me is my weekly newsletter and the guides and articles that I produce on my website.

103
00:07:14,720 --> 00:07:19,360
So every day what I'm trying to do is move people from Twitter and LinkedIn onto my website.

104
00:07:19,360 --> 00:07:21,360
Once I do that, it's pretty simple.

105
00:07:21,360 --> 00:07:23,919
Discovery, trust, expertise, and authority.

106
00:07:23,919 --> 00:07:25,919
And then it's a presentation of an offer.

107
00:07:25,919 --> 00:07:27,520
And my offers aren't aggressive.

108
00:07:27,520 --> 00:07:30,160
It's not like, "Hey, you need to buy my course right now.

109
00:07:30,160 --> 00:07:30,800
Urgency."

110
00:07:30,800 --> 00:07:41,360
It's just like if you enjoyed this piece of long- form content, if you believe I'm the person that can help you solve the problems that you have in your social media content or your online business,

111
00:07:41,360 --> 00:07:45,360
then here are some affordable options that I have right now.

112
00:07:45,360 --> 00:07:46,639
That's my funnel.

113
00:07:46,639 --> 00:07:51,680
Social media for discovery, longer form newsletter for trust, authority, and expertise,

114
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:53,599
and then asking people to buy something.

115
00:07:53,599 --> 00:07:54,240
Pretty simple.

116
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:54,479
All right.

117
00:07:54,479 --> 00:07:57,360
So, Justin, you post a ton of content on social media.

118
00:07:57,360 --> 00:07:59,680
How do you come up with so many new ideas for great content?

119
00:07:59,680 --> 00:08:02,720
Yeah, I have a bunch of different ways that I I think of ideas.

120
00:08:02,720 --> 00:08:06,879
Some really common ones for me is I subscribe to a lot of aggregator newsletters.

121
00:08:06,879 --> 00:08:10,560
So, every morning in my inbox, I get, you know, some of the biggest stories.

122
00:08:10,560 --> 00:08:14,240
I get some of my favorite creators bringing some of their things into my inbox.

123
00:08:14,240 --> 00:08:22,240
Uh, I look at a lot of YouTube channels that are relevant to to what I do, and I look at their most popular videos because if it's a popular video on YouTube,

124
00:08:22,240 --> 00:08:24,720
then it's probably going to resonate with my audience.

125
00:08:24,720 --> 00:08:28,000
I'm always looking for things that I can put my spin on, right?

126
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:31,120
You don't want to write the same thing that somebody else in your industry wrote.

127
00:08:31,120 --> 00:08:32,640
You want to take popular topics.

128
00:08:32,640 --> 00:08:36,159
You want to take things that are challenging to my ideal customer.

129
00:08:36,159 --> 00:08:38,399
And I want to put my spin on those things.

130
00:08:38,399 --> 00:08:40,080
I take ideas from everywhere.

131
00:08:40,080 --> 00:08:41,760
Podcasts I listen to.

132
00:08:41,760 --> 00:08:43,919
When I go on a walk, things pop into my head.

133
00:08:43,919 --> 00:08:45,680
So, I use my phone to capture things.

134
00:08:45,680 --> 00:08:51,200
I I'm always trying to be cognizant that ideation is around you at all times.

135
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:55,519
And if you let it slip by without noting it down, I can never remember them.

136
00:08:55,519 --> 00:08:58,000
So, I just try and keep track of them as they're happening.

137
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:00,399
What's a typical day in the life look like for you?

138
00:09:00,399 --> 00:09:02,000
My days are relatively regimented.

139
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,360
I wake up 5:30, 6, sometimes 6:30.

140
00:09:05,360 --> 00:09:08,480
I have a standing date with social media every morning.

141
00:09:08,480 --> 00:09:13,279
So, my content comes out at the exact same time every single morning, 8:15 Eastern time on both platforms,

142
00:09:13,279 --> 00:09:14,480
LinkedIn and Twitter.

143
00:09:14,480 --> 00:09:19,600
And I make it a point to engage with my audience almost every single morning for at least 45 minutes to an hour.

144
00:09:19,600 --> 00:09:23,360
Once I'm done with that, my wife and I, we got to go to the gym.

145
00:09:23,360 --> 00:09:28,800
And so we drive about 20 minutes down to the nearest town called Stone Ridge and we go to a gym there.

146
00:09:28,800 --> 00:09:35,200
So we might spend 9:30 till, you know, 11 at the gym and driving.

147
00:09:35,200 --> 00:09:38,720
And then we eat lunch, you know, around 11:30, 12.

148
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:44,480
And I don't really start doing creative work till normally around noon or 1:00 p.m.

149
00:09:44,480 --> 00:09:45,200
each day.

150
00:09:45,200 --> 00:09:48,720
And I'll try and do like a really intense 3 or 4 hours.

151
00:09:48,720 --> 00:09:52,560
And a typical uh, you know, day for that might be Monday.

152
00:09:52,560 --> 00:09:54,480
I'll spend that time writing my newsletter.

153
00:09:54,480 --> 00:09:58,399
Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday, I'll spend that time creating content.

154
00:09:58,399 --> 00:10:01,839
And Friday, I'll work towards more strategic projects.

155
00:10:01,839 --> 00:10:10,800
So, building a new product, um, you know, standing up a new service, working to meet interesting and unique people like you or like other folks who I uh,

156
00:10:10,800 --> 00:10:12,880
you know, admire on Twitter and LinkedIn.

157
00:10:12,880 --> 00:10:19,000
That's usually how I spend my Fridays, but that's a pretty typical and average week.

158
00:10:21,839 --> 00:10:25,120
It's really impressed me how fast you've built this business.

159
00:10:25,120 --> 00:10:29,519
How do you level up and how have you been able to grow so quickly?

160
00:10:29,519 --> 00:10:34,079
Back in 2018 when I first started giving this a swing, Russell Brunson was really popular,

161
00:10:34,079 --> 00:10:41,360
so I bought a lot of his books and that kind of gave me the fundamentals or the foundation for understanding why people change,

162
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:44,000
why people buy things, how to tell stories.

163
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:49,360
The way that I have leveled up is I'm a hypothesisdriven creator.

164
00:10:49,360 --> 00:10:54,640
Same thing I was when I was a sales leader in my my previous career, which meant making a hypothesis,

165
00:10:54,640 --> 00:10:56,240
testing it, seeing if it worked.

166
00:10:56,240 --> 00:11:00,560
If it did, doing it twice as much or three times as much or five times as much, and if it didn't,

167
00:11:00,560 --> 00:11:01,680
completely eliminating it.

168
00:11:01,680 --> 00:11:05,360
So, what I always encourage people to do is try a bunch of stuff.

169
00:11:05,360 --> 00:11:06,000
Try things.

170
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:08,079
Throw everything you can against the wall.

171
00:11:08,079 --> 00:11:11,360
That's the easiest path to getting better at this very specific business.

172
00:11:11,360 --> 00:11:11,600
Yeah.

173
00:11:11,600 --> 00:11:18,880
What advice would you have for someone that wants to do something similar or wants to get started building a a brand online and and selling products?

174
00:11:18,880 --> 00:11:27,200
The first thing I would I would do is is really think kind of deep and hard about what it is that you love doing that you're also very competent at.

175
00:11:27,200 --> 00:11:28,880
So figure out what that thing is.

176
00:11:28,880 --> 00:11:32,320
Talk to your friends, talk to your family, and go start talking about it online.

177
00:11:32,320 --> 00:11:35,600
The number one piece of advice I have for people is start.

178
00:11:35,600 --> 00:11:37,600
Everyone wants to learn everything.

179
00:11:37,600 --> 00:11:42,000
Everyone wants to read every book or listen to every podcast or do whatever.

180
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:52,079
Starting will teach you a hundred times more than reading my story or listening to what I have to say because your journey and everyone else's journey is going to be very different

181
00:11:52,079 --> 00:11:53,040
than mine.

182
00:11:53,040 --> 00:11:55,680
All advice is contextual, mine included.

183
00:11:55,680 --> 00:11:58,399
Start, learn, try.

184
00:11:58,399 --> 00:11:59,920
Yeah, that's great.

185
00:11:59,920 --> 00:12:00,800
Thank you.

186
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:04,000
Let's go.
